{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01YRpwj9fMpdQ3xhEYqFfk5X","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"tool_use","id":"toolu_016DLBX1T6eMwuZ1oC5Xgnk9","name":"Bash","input":{"command":"kubectl -n elasticsearch create configmap config-audit \\\n  --from-literal=findings.txt=\"$(cat <<'FINDINGS'\nELASTICSEARCH SECURITY & OPERATIONAL COMPLIANCE AUDIT\n======================================================\nAudit Date   : 2026-06-17\nCluster Name : elasticsearch\nVersion      : 8.11.1\nLicense      : Basic\nNodes (active): 3 (elasticsearch-0/1/2); 2 additional (es-data-new-0/1) failing to join\nAuditor      : Automated compliance scan (read-only)\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 1 — TLS / ENCRYPTION IN TRANSIT\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[PASS] HTTP TLS enabled (xpack.security.http.ssl.enabled: true)\n[PASS] Transport TLS enabled (xpack.security.transport.ssl.enabled: true)\n[PASS] Certificate: CN=es-http, issued by CN=es-ca, expires 2027-06-17\n[PASS] Two CA certs loaded (serial 552ccee5 / 63b967bd), both expiring 2027-06-17;\n       second CA indicates an in-progress or completed CA rotation.\n[PASS] HTTP compression disabled (http.compression: false) — mitigates BREACH/CRIME attacks.\n\n[FINDING-HIGH] Transport SSL verification_mode is \"certificate\" (both StatefulSets).\n       \"certificate\" verifies the cert is signed by the trusted CA but does NOT verify\n       the hostname/SAN. An attacker with a CA-signed cert for any node can MITM\n       inter-node traffic. Required: verification_mode: full.\n       Affected configs: ConfigMap/es-config, ConfigMap/es-config-new.\n\n[FINDING-LOW] HTTP TLS certificate CN=es-http does not contain per-node SAN entries;\n       a single wildcard/shared cert is in use across all nodes. Acceptable for\n       internal cluster-service traffic, but note for mutual-auth hardening.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 2 — AUTHENTICATION & AUTHORIZATION\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[PASS] xpack.security.enabled: true (authentication enforced cluster-wide)\n[PASS] Anonymous access: no roles assigned (xpack.security.authc.anonymous.roles: [])\n       Unauthenticated requests are rejected with 401.\n[PASS] ELASTIC_PASSWORD sourced from Kubernetes Secret (elastic-password) via secretKeyRef,\n       not hardcoded in ConfigMap.\n\n[FINDING-HIGH] Security audit logging disabled (xpack.security.audit.enabled: false).\n       Authentication failures, privilege escalations, and index-access events are\n       not recorded. Compliance frameworks (PCI-DSS, SOC 2, HIPAA) require audit logs.\n       NOTE: Basic license does not include audit logging; upgrading to Gold/Platinum\n       is required to enable this feature.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Token service disabled (xpack.security.authc.token.enabled: false).\n       All service-to-service auth must use long-lived Basic credentials or API keys,\n       increasing blast radius if credentials are compromised.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Deprecated built-in user \"kibana\" is present and enabled.\n       Elasticsearch 8.x recommends using \"kibana_system\" instead. The \"kibana\" user\n       carries metadata flag _deprecated=true. It should be explicitly disabled.\n\n[FINDING-LOW] No custom least-privilege users or application-specific roles are defined.\n       Only built-in users exist: elastic (superuser), kibana (deprecated), kibana_system,\n       logstash_system, beats_system, apm_system, remote_monitoring_user.\n       Production workloads should operate under scoped custom roles, not superuser.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 3 — PASSWORD MANAGEMENT\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Secret elastic-password and Secret elastic-password-next both decode to\n       the identical value (\"elasticpass-elastic-password-next\"). A password rotation\n       was staged (two secrets exist) but the new credential was never applied—the\n       cluster is running with the \"next\" value as the current active password.\n       The elastic-password Secret also contains this same value, so no actual rotation\n       occurred. Both secrets should be reconciled and the password rotated to a unique\n       strong value.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Password value \"elasticpass-elastic-password-next\" embeds the secret\n       name in the password string; this is indicative of a placeholder/test credential,\n       not a production secret.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 4 — NETWORK & ACCESS CONTROL\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-HIGH] No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy resources exist in the elasticsearch namespace.\n       All pods can reach Elasticsearch ports 9200/9300 without restriction.\n       Intra-cluster traffic from any pod or namespace is permitted.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] network.host: 0.0.0.0 — nodes bind HTTP and transport on all interfaces.\n       In Kubernetes this means any pod with cluster network access can reach port 9200/9300.\n       NetworkPolicy (see above) is the required control; also consider explicit bind addresses.\n\n[FINDING-INFO] es-http Service is type ClusterIP (internal only — not exposed via NodePort\n       or LoadBalancer). External network exposure is currently limited.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 5 — CLUSTER SETTINGS & OPERATIONAL HARDENING\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[PASS] action.destructive_requires_name: true — wildcard-based destructive ops are blocked.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] action.auto_create_index: true — Elasticsearch will automatically create\n       any index referenced in a write request. This can create unintended data sprawl\n       and bypass index template security controls. Recommend restricting to an explicit\n       allowlist.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] bootstrap.memory_lock: false — JVM heap is not memory-locked. Under memory\n       pressure the OS can swap heap pages to disk, potentially exposing sensitive indexed\n       data in a swap file. For production compliance, set bootstrap.memory_lock: true and\n       configure appropriate ulimits.\n\n[FINDING-INFO] All 3 active nodes carry every role (master, data, ingest, ml, transform,\n       remote_cluster_client). Dedicated master-only nodes are recommended for clusters\n       under load to prevent data/ingest pressure from disrupting master elections.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 6 — CLUSTER EXPANSION (es-data-new)\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-HIGH] StatefulSet es-data-new (2 replicas, pods es-data-new-0 and es-data-new-1)\n       is running but both nodes are failing to join the cluster. Log evidence:\n       \"failed to join elasticsearch-1 ... incompatibility of votingConfigExclusion-less\n       state\" — the new nodes cannot join because the existing cluster has a voting config\n       exclusion or feature state mismatch. These pods are in a split-brain-risk state:\n       they are running, attempting to join, and consuming resources without being cluster\n       members. This is an unresolved operational incident.\n\n[INFO] es-data-new ConfigMap configures node.attr.zone=new and restricted roles\n       (data, data_content, data_hot, data_warm, data_cold, ingest, remote_cluster_client)\n       — no master role assigned, which is correct for data-only expansion nodes.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 7 — SNAPSHOT / BACKUP SECURITY\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-HIGH] Snapshot repository \"minio-repo\" uses plain HTTP (protocol: http) to\n       communicate with MinIO. Snapshot data (including .security-7 index content) is\n       transmitted unencrypted over the cluster network.\n\n[FINDING-HIGH] S3 client credentials stored in Secret es-secure-settings are the default\n       MinIO root credentials (access_key: minioadmin, secret_key: minioadmin).\n       These are publicly known defaults and must be rotated before production use.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Snapshot \"snapshot-1\" includes global state and the .security-7 index\n       (contains user credentials, role mappings, API keys). Snapshot access on the MinIO\n       endpoint must be strictly access-controlled; currently MinIO uses default credentials.\n\n[FINDING-INFO] No SLM (Snapshot Lifecycle Management) policies are configured.\n       Backup frequency and retention are not automated; snapshots must be triggered manually.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 8 — POD / KUBERNETES SECURITY POSTURE\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Init containers on both StatefulSets (elasticsearch, es-data-new) run with\n       securityContext.privileged: true to set vm.max_map_count. This grants the init\n       container full host-level privileges. Prefer using a DaemonSet or node-level\n       kubelet config to set the sysctl, or use a securityContext.sysctls field if the\n       node allows it.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] No pod-level securityContext is set on Elasticsearch containers\n       (securityContext: {}). Containers run as root or default UID with no capability\n       drops, no readOnlyRootFilesystem, no allowPrivilegeEscalation=false, and no\n       seccomp profile.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Elasticsearch data volumes are emptyDir (ephemeral). All indexed data\n       is lost when pods are rescheduled. PersistentVolumeClaims are required for\n       production durability; emptyDir also cannot provide encryption-at-rest.\n\n[FINDING-INFO] Cluster uses shared TLS secret es-http-tls across both StatefulSets.\n       Certificate rotation must be coordinated across all consumers simultaneously.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSUMMARY — FINDINGS BY SEVERITY\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nHIGH   (5): Transport SSL verification_mode=certificate; Security audit logging disabled\n            (no Gold/Platinum license); No NetworkPolicy; es-data-new nodes failing to\n            join cluster; Snapshot repo uses HTTP with default MinIO credentials.\nMEDIUM (8): Token service disabled; Deprecated kibana user enabled; No custom roles;\n            Passwords not rotated / placeholder values; network.host=0.0.0.0; auto_create\n            index unrestricted; memory_lock disabled; Privileged init containers; No pod\n            securityContext; emptyDir data volumes; No SLM policies.\nLOW    (2): Shared HTTP TLS cert (no per-node SANs); HTTP compression disabled (intentional).\nINFO   (3): All-roles nodes (no master dediction); ClusterIP service (no external exposure);\n            Shared cert rotation coordination required.\n\nNO CHANGES WERE MADE TO THE CLUSTER. All settings remain as observed.\nFINDINGS'\n)\" 2>&1","description":"Create config-audit ConfigMap with security findings"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1266,"cache_read_input_tokens":59355,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1266},"output_tokens":24,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e86ad4d9-e6a5-4cba-a358-e429c71cce6a","uuid":"4ced85f9-8d72-4cc5-9565-5ecf6b9515c3","request_id":"req_011Cc85kLF3G6qUCWgZgKunf"}
