tation\n       was staged (two secrets exist) but the new credential was never applied; the\n       cluster is running the \"next\" value as the current active password. No actual\n       rotation occurred. Both secrets should be reconciled and the password rotated\n       to a unique, strong, randomly-generated value.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Password value \"elasticpass-elastic-password-next\" embeds the secret\n       name in the password string — indicative of a placeholder/test credential, not\n       a production secret. Must be replaced before any production use.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 4 — NETWORK & ACCESS CONTROL\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-HIGH] No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy resources exist in the elasticsearch namespace.\n       All pods can reach Elasticsearch ports 9200/9300 without restriction. Intra-cluster\n       traffic from any pod or namespace is permitted.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] network.host: 0.0.0.0 — nodes bind HTTP and transport on all interfaces.\n       In Kubernetes this means any pod with cluster network access can reach port 9200/9300.\n       NetworkPolicy (above) is the required compensating control.\n\n[INFO] es-http Service is type ClusterIP (internal only — not exposed via NodePort or\n       LoadBalancer). External network exposure is currently limited to in-cluster traffic.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 5 — CLUSTER SETTINGS & OPERATIONAL HARDENING\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[PASS] action.destructive_requires_name: true — wildcard destructive operations are blocked.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] action.auto_create_index: true — Elasticsearch auto-creates any index\n       referenced in a write request. This can create unintended data sprawl and bypass\n       index template security controls. Recommend restricting to an explicit allowlist.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] bootstrap.memory_lock: false — JVM heap is not memory-locked. Under memory\n       pressure the OS can swap heap pages to disk, potentially exposing sensitive indexed\n       data in a swap file. Remediation: set bootstrap.memory_lock: true with appropriate\n       ulimits (requires host-level configuration).\n\n[INFO] All 3 active nodes carry every role (master, data, ingest, ml, transform,\n       remote_cluster_client). Dedicated master-only nodes are recommended for clusters\n       under load to prevent data/ingest pressure from disrupting master elections.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 6 — CLUSTER EXPANSION (es-data-new)\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-HIGH] StatefulSet es-data-new (2 replicas: es-data-new-0, es-data-new-1) is\n       running but both nodes are continuously failing to join the cluster. Node logs show:\n       \"failed to join elasticsearch-1 with JoinRequest{sourceNode={es-data-new-0}...}\"\n       These nodes are in a split-brain-risk state: running, consuming resources, and\n       retrying joins without becoming cluster members. This is an unresolved operational\n       incident requiring remediation.\n\n[INFO] es-data-new ConfigMap configures node.attr.zone=new and restricted roles\n       (data, data_content, data_hot, data_warm, data_cold, ingest, remote_cluster_client)\n       with no master role — correct topology for data-only expansion nodes.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 7 — SNAPSHOT / BACKUP SECURITY\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-HIGH] Snapshot repository \"minio-repo\" uses plain HTTP (protocol: http) to\n       communicate with MinIO. Snapshot data (including .security-7 index content) is\n       transmitted unencrypted over the internal cluster network.\n\n[FINDING-HIGH] S3 client credentials in Secret es-secure-settings are the default MinIO\n       root credentials (access_key: minioadmin, secret_key: minioadmin). These are\n       publicly known defaults and must be rotated before any production use.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Snapshot \"snapshot-1\" includes global cluster state and the .security-7\n       index (contains user credentials, role mappings, API keys). Snapshot storage on\n       MinIO must be strictly access-controlled; currently MinIO uses default credentials.\n\n[INFO] No SLM (Snapshot Lifecycle Management) policies are configured. Backup frequency\n       and retention are not automated; snapshots must be triggered manually.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSECTION 8 — POD / KUBERNETES SECURITY POSTURE\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Init containers on both StatefulSets run with securityContext.privileged:\n       true to execute \"sysctl -w vm.max_map_count=262144\". This grants full host-level\n       privileges to the init container. Prefer a DaemonSet or node-level kubelet config\n       to set the sysctl, or use a pod-level sysctls field if the node allows it.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] No pod-level securityContext is configured on Elasticsearch containers\n       (securityContext: {}). Containers run without capability drops, no readOnly\n       rootFilesystem, no allowPrivilegeEscalation=false, and no seccomp/AppArmor profile.\n\n[FINDING-MEDIUM] Elasticsearch data volumes are emptyDir (ephemeral). All indexed data\n       is lost when pods are rescheduled. PersistentVolumeClaims are required for\n       production durability. emptyDir also cannot provide encryption-at-rest controls.\n\n[INFO] Shared TLS secret es-http-tls is mounted across both StatefulSets. Certificate\n       rotation must be coordinated across all consumers simultaneously.\n\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nSUMMARY — FINDINGS BY SEVERITY\n------------------------------------------------------------------------\nHIGH   (5):\n  1. Transport SSL verification_mode=certificate (MITM risk on inter-node traffic)\n  2. Security audit logging disabled; Basic license does not support audit logging\n  3. No Kubernetes NetworkPolicy (unrestricted pod-to-ES access)\n  4. es-data-new nodes failing to join cluster (operational incident)\n  5. Snapshot repo uses HTTP + default MinIO credentials (minioadmin/minioadmin)\n\nMEDIUM (8):\n  6.  Token service disabled (long-lived credential exposure risk)\n  7.  Deprecated \"kibana\" user enabled\n  8.  No custom least-privilege roles\n  9.  Passwords not rotated; both secrets hold identical placeholder value\n  10. action.auto_create_index unrestricted\n  11. bootstrap.memory_lock disabled (heap swappable to disk)\n  12. Privileged init containers on all nodes\n  13. No pod securityContext / capability drops\n  14. emptyDir data volumes (non-persistent, no encryption-at-rest)\n\nLOW    (1):\n  15. Shared HTTP TLS cert (no per-node SANs)\n\nINFO   (3):\n  - ClusterIP service only (no external exposure)\n  - All-role nodes (no dedicated master nodes)\n  - No SLM policies (manual snapshot management)\n\nNO CHANGES WERE MADE TO THE CLUSTER DURING THIS AUDIT.\nAll live settings remain exactly as observed. Remediation to be scheduled separately.\n"},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3831,"cache_read_input_tokens":60621,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3831},"output_tokens":23,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"e86ad4d9-e6a5-4cba-a358-e429c71cce6a","uuid":"13839410-f55c-415b-94ea-6e318bf18cd3","request_id":"req_011Cc85qqGvcKT6MRrHTwEvF"}
